Five minutes make all the difference to Yeoville’s early morning harmonies. Still wrapped in inky darkness at 4.30am, the streets are almost completely quiet. Animals make the only sounds. A scurrying rat here, the song of an early bird there. But by 4.35am, the tone has changed. Gates to apartment blocks creak open and the crunch of rubber soles treading on tarmac announce the morning commutes of essential workers.



On some days, two of those pairs of feet belong to lifelong friends Mercy Mokgehle and Zandile Mbatha. Mokgehle has sold vegetables in the Yeoville Market since 2004, and Mbatha for almost a decade longer than that. When South Africa’s nationwide Covid-19 lockdown began on 27 March, they feared the worst. “Remember, we live hand-to-mouth,” says Mokgehle. Without income or savings, they began to feed their families what vegetables were left over in their stalls. 



<img data-attachment-id="35714" data-permalink="https://www.newframe.com/not-all-joburgs-street-traders-are-trading/18may_streettraders_dw-2/" data-orig-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-2.jpg" data-orig-size="1800,1200" data-comments-opened="0" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;2.8&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;X-T20&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;8 May 2020: An empty Yeoville street before the early morning traffic of the neighbourhood\u2019s many essential workers.&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1588912933&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;\u00a9 New Frame&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;18.8&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;3200&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0.05&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="18May_StreetTraders_DW-2" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-2-960x640.jpg" data-large-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-2-1440x960.jpg" src="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-2.jpg" alt="8 May 2020: An empty Yeoville street before the neighbourhood’s many essential workers ring in the early morning traffic." class="wp-image-35714" srcset="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-2.jpg 1800w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-2-960x640.jpg 960w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-2-1440x960.jpg 1440w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-2-768x512.jpg 768w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-2-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-2-480x320.jpg 480w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-2-270x180.jpg 270w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-2-560x373.jpg 560w" sizes="(max-width: 1800px) 100vw, 1800px" />8 May 2020: An empty Yeoville street before the neighbourhood’s many essential workers ring in the early morning traffic.



Since 2 April, however, when South Africa took the lead with countries like Peru and Ghana in declaring street traders an essential service during Covid-19 lockdowns, Mokgehle and Mbatha have resumed their semiweekly, predawn trips to the Joburg Market in City Deep, south of Johannesburg, to replenish their stocks.



Weakest links



The two pay R30 for a trip on the back of a bakkie, packed shoulder-to-shoulder with other traders wrapped up against the autumnal chill. They are wary of the proximity – Mbatha makes sure everyone is wearing their face masks – but at this time of day during the lockdown, safer transport is impossible to come by.



Joburg’s skyline, etched out in Berea and Hillbrow apartment lights, whips past as they leave the city behind and cross into its mining belt. They pass trucking yards, stacks of shipping containers, ghostly, mustard-coloured mine dumps, and eventually arrive at the City Deep market.



<img data-attachment-id="35716" data-permalink="https://www.newframe.com/not-all-joburgs-street-traders-are-trading/8-may-2020-mercy-mokgehle-perusing-fresh-produce-at-the-city-deep-market/" data-orig-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-3.jpg" data-orig-size="1800,1200" data-comments-opened="0" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;2.8&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;X-T20&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;8 May 2020: Mercy Mokgehle perusing fresh produce at the City Deep market.&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1588917020&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;\u00a9 New Frame&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;18&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;800&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0.022222222222222&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;8 May 2020: Mercy Mokgehle perusing fresh produce at the City Deep market.&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="8 May 2020: Mercy Mokgehle perusing fresh produce at the City Deep market." data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-3-960x640.jpg" data-large-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-3-1440x960.jpg" src="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-3.jpg" alt="8 May 2020: Mercy Mokgehle perusing fresh produce at the City Deep fresh produce market." class="wp-image-35716" srcset="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-3.jpg 1800w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-3-960x640.jpg 960w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-3-1440x960.jpg 1440w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-3-768x512.jpg 768w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-3-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-3-480x320.jpg 480w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-3-270x180.jpg 270w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-3-560x373.jpg 560w" sizes="(max-width: 1800px) 100vw, 1800px" />8 May 2020: Mercy Mokgehle perusing fresh produce at the City Deep fresh produce market.



A city within a city, the market is a logistical behemoth. The avenues of potatoes, boroughs of onions and precincts of tomatoes that make up its warehouses have travelled along food supply chains that stretch from South Africa’s countryside and eventually on to its dinner plates. It is difficult to overstate the importance that street traders like Mokgehle and Mbatha play in these supply chains, and to South Africa’s food security more broadly.



By the Quarterly Labour Force Survey count, almost half a million people were involved in the informal retailing of food in South Africa before the onset of the coronavirus pandemic. According to Potatoes South Africa, almost one in every three potatoes in South Africa is sold by a street trader.



It’s no different in Johannesburg. Around half of the R7.5 billion in fresh produce sold every year at City Deep, according to Marc Wegerif at the University of Pretoria’s development studies department, goes to informal traders. An African Food Security Urban Network survey found that almost nine in every 10 Johannesburg households normally get their food from informal markets or street traders.



<img data-attachment-id="35720" data-permalink="https://www.newframe.com/not-all-joburgs-street-traders-are-trading/8-may-2020-mercy-mokgehle-makes-a-purchase-at-the-city-deep-market/" data-orig-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-5.jpg" data-orig-size="1800,1200" data-comments-opened="0" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;2.8&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;X-T20&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;8 May 2020: Mercy Mokgehle makes a purchase at the City Deep market.&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1588922282&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;\u00a9 New Frame&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;18.8&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;1250&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0.008&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;8 May 2020: Mercy Mokgehle makes a purchase at the City Deep market.&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="8 May 2020: Mercy Mokgehle makes a purchase at the City Deep market." data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-5-960x640.jpg" data-large-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-5-1440x960.jpg" src="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-5.jpg" alt="8 May 2020: Mercy Mokgehle makes a purchase at the City Deep market." class="wp-image-35720" srcset="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-5.jpg 1800w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-5-960x640.jpg 960w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-5-1440x960.jpg 1440w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-5-768x512.jpg 768w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-5-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-5-480x320.jpg 480w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-5-270x180.jpg 270w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-5-560x373.jpg 560w" sizes="(max-width: 1800px) 100vw, 1800px" />8 May 2020: Mercy Mokgehle makes a purchase at the City Deep market.



Beyond feeding the city, there are other ways in which the informal food system is well geared for the Covid-19 moment, according to Caroline Skinner, a senior researcher at the University of Cape Town’s African Centre for Cities. Often located outdoors and in impoverished communities, informal food retailers – spaza shops and street traders – cut the distance people need to travel to buy food, keeping them off crowded public transport and out of supermarket queues, for instance.



Mokgehle piles a trolley high with carrots, tomatoes, broccoli, cauliflowers, green peppers, cabbages, pumpkins and okra. Business has been unexpectedly good since she began trading again in early April. The limited number of trading permits being issued by the municipality has meant less competition and she is currently earning up to three times as much as she was before the lockdown



Hunger in the stomach



Mokgehle’s lockdown fortune is only one side of the coin, however. On the other side is Linah Malefahlo, who shares a rundown room with her youngest daughter and three grandchildren a few blocks from where the Yeoville Market has reopened.



<img data-attachment-id="35718" data-permalink="https://www.newframe.com/not-all-joburgs-street-traders-are-trading/18may_streettraders_dw-4/" data-orig-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-4.jpg" data-orig-size="1800,1200" data-comments-opened="0" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;4&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;X-T20&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;8 May 2020: Linah Malefahlo, 65, stands with some of the stock that has started to rot in her yard since being forced off of the sidewalks where she ordinarily makes her living.&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1588928717&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;\u00a9 New Frame&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;18&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;400&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0.013333333333333&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="18May_StreetTraders_DW-4" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-4-960x640.jpg" data-large-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-4-1440x960.jpg" src="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-4.jpg" alt="8 May 2020: Linah Malefahlo with some of the fresh produce that has started to rot in her yard since she was forced off the sidewalks, where she ordinarily trades for a living." class="wp-image-35718" srcset="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-4.jpg 1800w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-4-960x640.jpg 960w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-4-1440x960.jpg 1440w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-4-768x512.jpg 768w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-4-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-4-480x320.jpg 480w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-4-270x180.jpg 270w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-4-560x373.jpg 560w" sizes="(max-width: 1800px) 100vw, 1800px" />8 May 2020: Linah Malefahlo with some of the fresh produce that has started to rot in her yard since she was forced off the sidewalks, where she ordinarily trades for a living.



Unable to secure one of the limited trading spaces in the Yeoville Market, Malefahlo ordinarily sells vegetables from the neighbourhood’s sidewalks. But despite being granted a permit by the City of Johannesburg’s Department of Economic Development to trade during the lockdown, City officials have refused to allow her to trade on the sidewalk. She has resorted to selling small bags of wild spinach covertly on street corners and, at the age of 65, running away from City officials if they arrive. Meanwhile, Malefahlo’s stock is rotting in her yard. She has been forced to sell sacks of potatoes, for which she paid R65, to spaza shops operating deep fryers for R50.



Two central pillars in Malefahlo’s economic life have crumbled under lockdown. She cannot meet with the members of her weekly stokvel and, without a steady income, she is no longer able to support her family living in rural Limpopo province.



<img data-attachment-id="35722" data-permalink="https://www.newframe.com/not-all-joburgs-street-traders-are-trading/18may_streettraders_dw-6/" data-orig-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-6.jpg" data-orig-size="1800,1200" data-comments-opened="0" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;3.2&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;X-T20&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;CityDeep - 8 May 2020: The City Deep fresh produce market - a city within a city.&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1588922878&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;\u00a9 New Frame&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;20.5&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;800&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0.016666666666667&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="18May_StreetTraders_DW-6" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-6-960x640.jpg" data-large-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-6-1440x960.jpg" src="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-6.jpg" alt="8 May 2020: The City Deep fresh produce market is a city within a city." class="wp-image-35722" srcset="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-6.jpg 1800w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-6-960x640.jpg 960w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-6-1440x960.jpg 1440w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-6-768x512.jpg 768w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-6-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-6-480x320.jpg 480w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-6-270x180.jpg 270w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-6-560x373.jpg 560w" sizes="(max-width: 1800px) 100vw, 1800px" />8 May 2020: The City Deep fresh produce market is a city within a city.



<img data-attachment-id="35724" data-permalink="https://www.newframe.com/not-all-joburgs-street-traders-are-trading/18may_streettraders_dw-7/" data-orig-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-7.jpg" data-orig-size="1800,1200" data-comments-opened="0" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;2.8&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;X-T20&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;8 May 2020: Avenues of potatoes at the City Deep fresh produce market. One in three potatoes in South Africa is sold by an informal trader.&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1588919987&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;\u00a9 New Frame&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;18&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;1600&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0.016666666666667&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="18May_StreetTraders_DW-7" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-7-960x640.jpg" data-large-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-7-1440x960.jpg" src="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-7.jpg" alt="8 May 2020: Avenues of potatoes at the City Deep market. One in three potatoes in South Africa is sold by a street trader." class="wp-image-35724" srcset="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-7.jpg 1800w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-7-960x640.jpg 960w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-7-1440x960.jpg 1440w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-7-768x512.jpg 768w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-7-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-7-480x320.jpg 480w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-7-270x180.jpg 270w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/18May_StreetTraders_DW-7-560x373.jpg 560w" sizes="(max-width: 1800px) 100vw, 1800px" />8 May 2020: Avenues of potatoes at the City Deep market. One in three potatoes in South Africa is sold by a street trader.



Remittances like those Malefahlo used to send every month are no longer as central to South Africa’s rural homes as they once were. Economists at the University of Cape Town’s South African Labour and Development Research Unit have shown that the proportion of South African households receiving remittances has decreased since 1993, when nearly one in every four homes received remittances. Nevertheless, in cases like Malefahlo’s, the lockdown has severed lifegiving economic links between the city and countryside.



“They will kill us,” says Malefahlo of the lockdown and, pointing to her grandchildren, that “these kids will do bad things because they are hungry in their stomachs”.



Remittances have declined as the importance of social grants to South Africa’s most impoverished households has grown. The newly minted Covid-19 Social Relief of Distress grant will bring informal workers into that social security net for the first time. The R350 per month, however, is “not going to cut it”, says Skinner. “It’s barely putting food on the table for two or three days.”



